RevigoR

Felix GM Ernst

2018-08-09

1 Introduction

Revigo (Supek 2011) is a web service (http://revigo.irb.hr/) for visualizing lists of gene ontology (GO) terms and their relation to each others. As input a list of gene ontology terms and optionally associated p-values are accepted. To access the information directly from a R session RevigoR can be used.

2 Get Revigo data

Their are several option to get the Revigo results. It largely depends, how the GO terms are stored. The simplest option is a data.frame with two columns for GO terms in the format GO:XXXXXX and their associated p-values.

data("rdinput", package = "RevigoR")
rdinput

rd <- getRevigo(rdinput)
rd
#> RevigoRData of length 2
#> names(2): table treemap

The results are saved as a RevigoData object, which is basically a SimpleList with a fixed length of two (table and treemap keays)

rd
#> RevigoRData of length 2
#> names(2): table treemap
all(getTableData(rd) == rd[["table"]], na.rm = TRUE)
#> [1] TRUE

For commonly used GO objects such as DAVIDFunctionalAnnotationChart from the RDAVIDWebService. Since a chart can hold data different GO categories, a category has to be chosen for subsetting.

data("chart", package = "RevigoR")
chart
# also 
rd <- getRevigo(chart,
                goCategory = "GOTERM_BP_DIRECT")
rd
#> RevigoRData of length 2
#> names(2): table treemap

3 Plot Revigo type figures

Results from Revigo are usually plotted as a scatter plot or treemap as done on the web site

plotRevigoScatter(rd)

Figure 1: Revigo scatter plot

plotRevigoTreemap(rd)

Figure 2: Revigo treemap plot
